# Architecture Boundaries LLM Guide

## Purpose

Use this command to validate the current codebase against the configured architecture agreement. It checks disallowed dependencies, layer flow, and cycle rules.

## When To Run

- Before changing cross-module imports.
- After moving code between layers.
- Before finishing any refactor that might affect dependency direction.

## How To Read The Result

- A passing result means no configured boundary violations were found.
- Edge rule findings point to a blocked source-to-target dependency.
- Flow findings point to a dependency path that moves against the configured layer direction.
- Cycle findings point to dependency loops that should be broken at the owning seam.

## Examples

- If a user-facing layer imports persistence behavior directly, move that access behind the application seam that owns the workflow.
- If one module imports another module's private implementation, switch to the target module's public seam or ask whether a public seam is missing.
- If a lower-level layer imports a higher-level orchestration layer, invert the dependency so orchestration calls inward.
- If two modules depend on each other, move shared policy to the true owner or introduce a narrower public handoff.
- If a violation appears only because a symbol was imported for convenience, prefer passing data through the existing owning workflow.

## Agent Tips

- Treat findings as blockers, not style advice.
- Fix the owning dependency direction instead of adding bypass imports.
- Prefer using a module's public seam when one exists.
- Rerun the command after each import or layer-ownership fix.
